That reminds me of something we did in another general way back. That one had a permanent shitposter too. Something that some of us started doing at some point was to sideline the shitposter with posts meant to spark a parallel line of conversation. Initially success was limited, but more and more started doing it and more and more were getting involved. Nobody organized it, it was a spontaneous vigilante movement powered by the desire to spite the shitposter. Every time he showed up we circled the wagons and the thread came alive with brilliant discussions and new content. Unfortunately that general was much larger, culturally rather different and this was years ago, so I'm not sure if this could happen here.

There has to be something in the plot, which is summarized by the hook, that is "at stake." What are the consequences of failure?

"The fate of the universe rests in the hands of one man." <--- the stake is the fate of the universe. Put that in your hook.

The "stake" and the "so what?" tests are fundamental parts of understanding your story. If you don't have anything at stake you don't have a story.

Take your favorite /hmofa/ story and see if you can find "the stake." You'll probably find that the best/most lasting stories in /hmofa/ history have something "at stake"

Anonymous Sat 03 Apr 2021 01:34:09 No.37606035 Report
Quoted By: >>37606211
>>37605380
>Not him but how to make a good summary/hook?
1!!!!!!!!!!) SO what? >>37605533
2) The less context to understand the summary the better.
3) Something that conveys the setting and why it's interesting.
4) Writing multiples summaries (practice summarizing and knowing your story)

You have stories like anon mentioned earlier like COTW, Greased Monkey that are real easy to write summaries for b/c the things that made them interesting were so easy to express that it immediately sprung a story. Then you have franchise stories like On the Fringes and the night stalker series, wherein the hook is basically helped along with the fact that it's a popular premise/waifur.

Then you have stories that are harder to write summaries for and the popularity of these stories was a combination of skill and persistence: Leaves of Fall, Happiest Place on Fur, and currently: HSR and in the burning heart. The former stories, especially Leaves of Fall, was not popular right at the start and frankly I don't know how it took off until I read it. For a time I thought it was just another dead story never to be finished. But I am diverting. Wizard? Courier? Marine? Veteran? Don't rely on just the occupation or a single word carry the context of your summary, if it's ordinary enough. If you can't put everything into the summary write it like that is the case, it might be hard to do since you wrote it, but one must know there story and why people should read it. This is analogous to an abstract to a research paper: there is almost no official guideline or procedure to do it, despite what people may tell you.


Basically, your summaries should be like high effort prompt posting: crafted in way to maximize clicks and (you)s
